## Verdict

**Do not commit this as P3-LR-SURG yet.** It is useful and mostly points toward the right Phase-1 design, but two load-bearing conclusions—the exact invariance characterization and the “well-defined strongest comparator”—are technically overstated. The Phase-1 hand-off consequently claims more closure than the review earned.

I found no obviously hallucinated paper among the sources spot-checked, including the recent 2026 papers. The problem is mainly inaccurate characterization, overconfident verification metadata, and unsupported extrapolation.

## Three most important concerns

1. **The invariance account contains a direct error and conflates two different symmetry questions.**

   [SURG.md:166](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SURG.md:166) says SliceGPT uses one global residual-stream \(Q\) and presents layer-specific \(Q_\ell\) as function-changing absent online transforms. SliceGPT explicitly permits a different \(Q_\ell\) at each block, introducing the corresponding \(Q_{\ell-1}^{T}Q_\ell\) transformation in the residual path. Therefore “consistent with SliceGPT/QuaRot, both of which use one residual-stream Q” is false. [SliceGPT paper](https://openreview.net/pdf?id=vXxardq6db)

   The review also conflates:

   - the checkpoint-coordinate gauge of an untouched parameterization;
   - function-preserving model reparameterizations after gain fusion or LayerNorm conversion;
   - layer-specific computational invariances with explicit residual-path transformations.

   The signed-permutation paper is real, but it is a very recent single-author preprint about coordinate transport. It does not justify treating \(B_d/S_d\) as the final answer to all transformer-surgery invariance questions. Its abstract also gives LayerNorm \(S_d\) **up to a global sign flip**, omitted in SURG. [Signed-Permutation Coordinate Transport](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.31963)

2. **The “strongest comparator” and matched-accounting conclusion are not established.**

   Minitron, Sheared-LLaMA and teacher correction are good ingredients, but [SURG.md:124](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SURG.md:124) invents a hybrid recipe—Minitron pruning + teacher correction + Sheared-LLaMA remixing—that no cited paper evaluates as a combined method. Calling it “well-defined and strong” is premature.

   More importantly:

   - Minitron’s reported from-scratch comparison is **iso-compute**, not equal-token: its table compares 100B KD tokens with 150B scratch tokens because KD includes teacher-forward cost. [Minitron §4.2/Table 11](https://arxiv.org/html/2407.14679)
   - The distillation scaling-law paper does not establish, without a calculation, that post-pruning KD at 135M/160M “MUST” dominate continued pretraining. Its result concerns regime-dependent compute-optimal distillation, not specifically tiny-model pruning recovery. [Distillation Scaling Laws](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.08606)
   - Evidence from 7B→1.3B and 15B→4B does not supply defensible non-inferiority margins for 135M/160M donors.
   - Teacher correction, importance search, dynamic remixing and recipe selection all consume tuning compute. Equal recovery tokens/FLOPs alone does not match that effort.
   - Quantization and the resource-frontier baseline remain outside this comparator, despite the programme requiring them elsewhere.

   The ledger’s conclusion that existing accounting rules are already adequate is therefore too strong.

3. **The Phase-1 hand-off marks unresolved matters as “settled.”**

   [SURG.md:483](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SURG.md:483) says the design bead should inherit several conclusions “not re-litigate,” including the incorrect global-\(Q\) account, the untested hybrid comparator, and adequate accounting. Those are exactly what P3-D-DD still needs to derive or pilot.

   The prior-art absence claim is appropriately called search-bounded, but neither the review nor `sources.jsonl` records search strings, databases, dates per query, or inclusion/exclusion results. It supports “no exact prior art located in this review,” not a durable novelty finding.

## Factual and citation errors

- **False:** SliceGPT uses one global \(Q\). It supports block-specific \(Q_\ell\) with residual-path bridge matrices.
- **False:** Minitron’s MMLU improvement is at equal token budget. The relevant comparison is iso-compute with unequal token counts.
- **Misstated:** QuaRot’s RoPE workaround rotates queries and keys online; its value-rotation path is separate. [QuaRot method](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.00456)
- **Overstated:** [SURG.md:220](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SURG.md:220) says near-zero loss barriers at billion-parameter scale. The paper reports near-zero barriers for medium-sized WikiText LMs and only small barriers for modern billion-parameter LLMs. [Linear Mode Connectivity paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.23607)
- **Incomplete:** LayerNorm’s cited gauge is \(S_d\) up to a global sign flip, not simply \(S_d\).
- **Misleading:** PCA minimizes calibration-activation reconstruction error, not model-output or downstream behavioral error.
- **Incorrect inference:** “Dropping \(N\) parameters requires backfilling \(\lesssim2N\) store bits.” The paper estimates maximum factual entropy stored per parameter under synthetic conditions. An external store needs addressing, keys, schema and retrieval overhead; \(2N\) is not an upper bound on packed store size. [Knowledge Capacity Scaling Laws](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.05405)
- **Wrong source title:** `lmlm-2505.15962` says “Limited Memory Language Models”; the paper is **Pre-training Large Memory Language Models with Internal and External Knowledge**. [LMLM paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.15962)
- **Ambiguous/misleading:** the ~11T-token statement belongs to SmolLM2-1.7B; the cited abstract does not establish that all 135M/360M/1.7B siblings received ~11T tokens. [SmolLM2 paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.02737)
- **Unsupported:** the R-1 recovery budget is asserted to fall inside KD’s winning regime without applying the cited scaling law.
- **Overclaimed verification:** `verified:true` means only author self-attestation here. The JSONL contains no page/section/table locators, excerpts, version dates or verification record; two `verified:true` entries explicitly contain unverified subclaims. “31 verified at primary source” is not auditable from the artifact.

## Phase-1 de-risking

The hand-off does contain several good safeguards:

- causal ablation before structural pruning;
- relevant/irrelevant task selectivity;
- two donors;
- random-subspace and generic-pruning controls;
- store-specific restoration;
- oracle/NLB labeling;
- measured bytes rather than width arithmetic.

But P3-D-DD should additionally be required to:

- derive both global and layer-specific invariances, including explicit residual bridges;
- validate every transformation with logits over a pinned corpus, not merely numerical checks per matrix;
- benchmark candidate compression recipes on the actual 135M/160M donors before choosing margins;
- count teacher correction, importance search, remixing and hyperparameter selection in tuning compute;
- treat super weights as a stratified/control variable, not automatically protect them;
- express the 2-bit result only as a synthetic information-capacity sanity bound;
- inherit the full P3-D-FRONTIER and generic-RAG controls before any superiority claim.

**Commit judgment: no.** Revise the invariance section, correct the source characterizations, downgrade the comparator/accounting conclusions, and change “settled/not re-litigate” to explicit Phase-1 hypotheses and derivation requirements. After those corrections, it would be a sound literature-review hand-off.